import javax.servlet.http.HttpServlet;
import javax.servlet.http.HttpServletRequest;
import javax.servlet.http.HttpServletResponse;
import java.io.IOException;

public class EnhancedSecurityHeadersServlet extends HttpServlet {
    protected void doGet(HttpServletRequest request, HttpServletResponse response) throws IOException {
        // Set security headers to enhance web application security

        // Prevent clickjacking by setting the X-Frame-Options header
        response.setHeader("X-Frame-Options", "DENY"); // This prevents the page from being displayed in a frame

        // Enforce HTTPS by setting the Strict-Transport-Security header
        response.setHeader("Strict-Transport-Security", "max-age=31536000; includeSubDomains"); // Enforces HTTPS for one year

        // Mitigate XSS vulnerabilities by setting the Content-Security-Policy header
        response.setHeader("Content-Security-Policy", "default-src 'self'; script-src 'self' https://trusted.cdn.com"); // Only allows scripts from self and trusted CDN

        // Additional security header to prevent MIME type sniffing
        response.setHeader("X-Content-Type-Options", "nosniff"); // Prevents browsers from MIME-sniffing a response away from the declared content-type

        // Additional security header to prevent cross-site scripting
        response.setHeader("X-XSS-Protection", "1; mode=block"); // Enables XSS filtering and blocks the page if an attack is detected

        response.getWriter().write("Enhanced security headers set successfully.");
    }
}
```

In the first code snippet, the `SecurityHeadersServlet` class demonstrates how to set basic security headers using the `HttpServletResponse` class. It includes headers to prevent clickjacking, enforce HTTPS, and mitigate XSS vulnerabilities.

In the second code snippet, the `EnhancedSecurityHeadersServlet` class builds upon the first by adding additional security headers. It includes the `X-Content-Type-Options` header to prevent MIME type sniffing and the `X-XSS-Protection` header to enable XSS filtering. These headers further enhance the security posture of the web application, making it more resilient against common web vulnerabilities.

